All may not be well with the Imo State House of Assembly as 22 members have allegedly endorsed impeachment proceedings against the speaker, Rt Hon Chiji Collins. Currently, the House was shut down for fumigation exercise following the infection of some lawmakers about two weeks ago. The member representing Oguta State constituency, Frank Ugboma, who spoke with newsmen said the speaker, Collins had turned the parliamentary arm to an extension of the executive. He disclosed that already, 22 lawmakers have endorsed the impeachment move against the speaker, adding that they are waiting for the House to reconvene, to invoke the House rules and do the needful. Ugboma said the 22 members have already asked the speaker to resign honourably or face impeachment any moment. According to him, their constituents had inundated them with complaints of delayed salaries and pensions, adding that even lawmakers were owed. He said while lawmakers are yet to receive their salaries, the speaker via the state owned newspaper, The Statesman said they had been paid, an action he said pitched them against their people. Ugboma said, “At various times, I have been inundated with calls and messages from many of such owed government employees and retirees from my constituency. Many times have I assured them, to no avail. Come to think of it, should I break the spirit of my constituents (who come to seek help), with the news that I am also owed salaries, even as member of the House of Assembly?”